The initial play we've taken has been to be better than anyone else at a thing that is in demand (inference), on top of bittensor with entirely open source code/open weight models, exposing the capabilities of the platform.  In 6 months we became one of the largest non-frontier inference provider on ~~openrouter~~ the planet and matched the direct usage of some of the web2 giants.

Now, we're starting to move away from that free/insanely rapid adoption trend being the main focus, since we've pretty clearly proven the capabilities of the platform, and starting to push more towards what chutes is fundamentally - serverless, arbitrary compute. Just like aws lambda/modal/replicate/etc., the actual hourly price for serverless compute *can be* at a premium because you only pay for what you use.

So while bare compute you can only ever charge the minimum industry rate per GPU, you can charge a higher premium for the service layer that abstracts it and does it per-per-use.  See cloudflare containers for example, or modal.com charging more than 2x hourly rate for GPUs, etc.  This is especially true with shared resources like we have on chutes, i.e. public chutes where concurrency > 1 allows serving multiple users concurrently but each would pay the same hourly rate. A service built on top of a GPU (like chutes) can serve multiple users but a rented GPU can only ever serve exactly one.

Our biggest barrier right now is privacy (lack of provable privacy that is), which we'll solve with TEE.

Also, apps built on top of chutes that make use of all of the chutes, vs. just LLM inference, can build higher margin revenue over time if the product is compelling enough, etc.

By burning, you artificially lower the alpha in the pool of course, which helps the "price" and therefore emissions, but it doesn't actually do anything to drive demand and/or usage of the actual product, so I think maybe that's slightly unaligned (should we really be spending time competing on who can best manipulate the liquidity?)

The question is really, do you burn/try to boost the token at the expense of the product (less incentive for miners to do what we/subnets are asking them to do) or boost the product at the cost of the token?

Personally I prefer using the alpha for the intended purpose of actually building the product, not trying to hinder the product's growth to inflate the token, but of course there needs to be a reasonable middle ground and I'm heavily biased having been a miner myself at one point.

That said, we do need to limit the amount of inventory on the platform, now that we've fully required some payment history to use chutes. We have far more supply than demand, so we can do some reasonable inventory control. The question then becomes, burn the rest and try to define some criteria by which we assign value to the miners, or do we try to find some way in which miners can keep the alpha regardless of the amount they would otherwise need to sell for inventory?

I think the only way to attract the best miners (depending on the subnet of course) is for great incentives, so burning them seems to be totally contrary to that goal.  My personal preference would be some means by which miners are able to keep the alpha but have it be locked away for example. In other words, I would love for miners to have the excess alpha by reducing the amount needed to sustain the inventory thereby allowing them to become investors themselves since they are theoretically some of the best investors, having skin in the game and intiment knowledge of the subnet.

For example, this could be something like a smart contract which limits the release of the funds to miners gradually over time, in exchange for a boost in incentives based on the proportion of your miner emissions you put towards this smart contract should you choose to opt-in (just as an example, and no it would not be a "ponzi" because the total amount staked would be irrelevant it would just be the proportion at any time you opt-in and a function of your incentive that would determine this boost). Miners are still incentivized then to reduce inventory to have healthy amount of contribution to smart contract which in turn still removes the alpha from the pool and helps tokenomics, but ultimately they still have ownership. Could they dump afterwards? I suppose yes, but ideally the ones who commit to these long term smart contracts are holders anyways, and less likely to do so.
